The article is a presidential proclamation by Barack Obama declaring June 17 through June 23, 2016, as the National Week of Making. The proclamation emphasizes the importance of innovation and entrepreneurship in driving the economy and transforming society. It highlights the maker movement and the democratization of technology, which have made it easier for people of all ages to connect and showcase their creativity. The proclamation also mentions the Nation of Makers initiative launched by Obama in 2014, which aims to provide more opportunities for Americans to design, build, and manufacture. It calls for the expansion of STEM education and active learning experiences to prepare young people for future jobs and increase diversity in STEM fields. The article encourages communities to support and promote making by ensuring spaces for creativity are available everywhere. The proclamation concludes by urging Americans to observe the National Week of Making through programs and activities that encourage a new generation of makers and manufacturers to share their talents and skills.